<paragraph blockId="21.[701,1228,1676,1759]" lastBlockId="24.[93,620,213,1759]" lastPageId="24" lastPageNumber="24" pageId="21" pageNumber="21">
ETYMOLOGY: The name 
<taxonomicName authority="González-Santillán &amp; Prendini, 2013" authorityName="González-Santillán &amp; Prendini" authorityYear="2013" box="[1041,1158,1677,1700]" class="Arachnida" family="Vaejovidae" genus="Balsateres" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="21" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1041,1158,1677,1700]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="21">Balsateres</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="21" pageNumber="21" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, a compound word, masculine in gender, is derived from the Balsas Depression, to which the genus is endemic, and the Latin adjective 
<emphasis box="[216,270,243,264]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="24">teres</emphasis>
(‘‘smooth’’ or ‘‘polished’’) which refers to the glabrous integument typical of this genus.
</paragraph>
